      "q": "Can a struct participate in a retain cycle, and can value types leak?",
      "a": "A pure value type with no reference-typed members can't participate in a retain cycle because it isn't reference counted at all. But the moment a struct stores a class reference or a closure, that reference can absolutely be part of a cycle — the struct is just along for the ride through its reference-typed field. A common real case is a struct holding a closure that captures an object which transitively holds the struct's storage. So 'structs can't leak' is only true for structs that contain no references.",
      "d": "Value semantics protect you from cycles only to the extent the value contains no references. A `struct` that captures `self` in a stored closure, or holds a class that points back through a chain to that closure's owner, forms a cycle through the heap-allocated parts. Closures are themselves reference types, so a struct with a closure property has a reference-counted member. Another angle: a struct captured by an escaping closure may be boxed onto the heap, and if that box ends up in a cycle, the struct's lifetime is affected. Indirect enums (`indirect enum`) also allocate heap storage and are reference-counted internally, so recursive enum structures can in principle leak through retained closures. The mental shortcut is to ask 'does this value transitively own any class or closure?' — if yes, it can be in a cycle; if no, it's cycle-immune. This is a strong argument for modeling state as plain value types where possible, which is partly why Swift and SwiftUI favor structs.",
