      "q": "Why must a class-bound protocol be used for `weak` delegates, and what breaks otherwise?",
      "a": "`weak` is a memory-management qualifier that only applies to reference types, because the whole mechanism — not contributing to the retain count and being zeroed on deallocation — only makes sense for heap-allocated reference-counted objects. If a protocol could be adopted by a struct, the compiler can't guarantee the conforming type is a class, so it won't let you mark the property `weak`. To make it work you constrain the protocol with `: AnyObject`, which guarantees only classes conform. Without that, you either can't use `weak` at all or you're forced into a strong reference that risks a cycle.",
      "d": "A `weak` reference needs side-table registration and zeroing, which require an object with ARC bookkeeping; value types have no such machinery, so `weak var` over an unconstrained protocol existential is rejected. Constraining with `: AnyObject` (formerly `class`) tells the compiler the existential always boxes a class instance, making the weak storage representable. Beyond the compile error, the deeper design reason is correctness: a delegate is an identity-based relationship where you want the relationship to evaporate if the delegate dies, which is exactly weak-zeroing semantics — meaningless for a copied struct. There's also a performance angle: class-bound existentials have a simpler representation than general existentials, avoiding the value-witness boxing overhead. If you genuinely need a value-type delegate, you'd model it differently — e.g., store a closure or use a strong reference with manual lifecycle — accepting the different ownership tradeoffs. So `: AnyObject` is both a requirement for `weak` and a statement of intent about identity and lifetime.",
